<DOCNO> AP890801-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after decades of hostility the vatican is 
seizing on what it calls a new spirit of cooperation by moscow to 
strengthen the roman catholic church in the soviet bloc 
over the past six months the vatican has succeeded in naming 
new bishops in lithuania and czechoslovakia forging diplomatic 
ties with poland after a 40year lapse and nailing down a visit by 
pope john paul ii to hungary 
and last week the vatican named its first bishop in the soviet 
republic of byelorussia since the aftermath of the russian 
revolution 
all the steps taken together are very important said a 
senior vatican diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity it 
is an encouraging picture 
vatican officials and independent analysts say progress is due 
to the combination of openings provided by soviet leader mikhail s 
gorbachev and a pragmatic policy pursued by the pope who as a 
bishop in poland had pursued a moderate but firm strategy for 
religious freedom 
the vatican is aware of the new opportunities and is putting 
out feelers in as many directions as it possibly can said dr 
john eibner head of eastern european research at keston college 
the british institute that monitors religious freedom around the 
world 
not everything is rosy despite the appointments last week of 
four bishops in czechoslovakia seven dioceses still lack bishops 
in romania there are no eastern rite catholic bishops 
in the soviet union a major obstacle to improved relations 
remains the ukrainian catholic church which was forcibly merged 
with the russian orthodox church under josef stalin in 1946 
there is a strong underground ukrainian church and ukrainian 
faithful have stepped up demands for recognition of their church 
but vatican officials dont expect any immediate solution 
still progress is unmistakable and has extended to soviet 
allies cuba which has agreed to a visit by the pope expected in 
two years and vietnam where a cardinal recently made the first 
official visit by a vatican representative since the communist 
takeover 
the appointment of a bishop to byelorussia is viewed as 
particularly significant since it is uncontested soviet territory 
the vatican does not recognize the absorption of lithuania by the 
soviet union in 1940 and a lithuanian exile mission is accredited 
to the holy see 
in the case of lithuania in march and in byelorussia last week 
the vatican informed the kremlin of the decision to appoint a 
bishop 
these authorities in the new spirit established by the 
soviet government politely let the holy father know they had no 
difficulty in this regard the vatican said 
experts are divided over whether moscow is sending out any 
direct signals to its allies or whether it is a situation of the 
winds of change blowing across borders and the church being seen as 
a potential partner in helping to rebuild shattered economies 
analysts do agree that the potential of a church without leaders 
was becoming increasingly embarrassing for the prague government 
which has been widely criticized for religious repression 
the vatican has made public note of the changed attitude of the 
soviet leadership toward religion and has been encouraging contacts 
pravda the soviet party newspaper said earlier this year that 
a bridge is being built from both sides the commentary was in 
marked contrast to accusations by soviet news media in the early 
80s that the pope and the church were interfering in polish affairs 
there is speculation that hungary may be the next warsaw pact 
country after poland to establish diplomatic ties with the holy 
see john paul recently told a group of hungarian pilgrims to 
prepare spiritually for my apostolic visit to hungary within two 
years 
how much progress is down the road could be answered when 
gorbachev visits italy in november and is expected to see the pope 
the meeting would be of historic proportions the first between 
the head of a soviet party that disparages religion and the leader 
of a church with 850 million followers 
it was stalin who cynically assessed the roman popes influence 
asking how many divisions does the pope have 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note victor simpson rome news editor has covered 
john paul iis papacy since the pontiff was elected in october 1978 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

