<TEXT>
rotating grain crops such as corn with 
alfalfa is a key strategy for sustaining agriculture in the long 
run according to a new study by the us department of agriculture 
and cornell university scientists 
crop rotation may be the answer to sustaining longterm 
productivity of our land to provide billions of people with food 
fuel and other renewable resources says gary h heichel a plant 
physiologist with the usdas agricultural research service 
he says the study analyzes energy uses of various farming 
systems including continuous corn crops and various rotations of 
grain and legume crops continuous corn can be highly productive 
with the use of nitrogen fertilizer he says adding but is of 
dubious sustainability because of high fossil fuel use and soil 
erosion 
on the other hand heichel said legumes are among the 
most efficient crops grown in the united states partly because 
little fuel is required to grow them also more energy is embodied 
in farming equipment needed to grow other crops such as corn 
more than 3 million calories of fossil fuel energy normally are 
required to produce nitrogen fertilizer for an acre of corn grown 
under a continuous cropping program said david pimentel an 
ecologist and entomologist at cornell university but a crop 
rotation that alternates one crop of soybeans which normally 
requires no nitrogen fertilizer with two crops of corn could 
reduce fossil energy use by 26 percent 
</TEXT>
