and endorsed by the party is designed to fight shortages by 
introducing freemarket mechanisms 
polands mainly private farmers who have cut back on profitless 
meat and grain sales to the state are free to sell to whomever 
they want at whatever prices they can negotiate as an incentive to 
increase production 
government food subsidies are to remain stable however and 
stateowned stores and food processors are supposed to pass their 
added purchasing costs to consumers 
solidarity and the independent farmers union rural solidarity 
backed the reform but oppose its rapid implementation 
there are no conditions for a free market to work said 
gabriel janowski of rural solidarity he said that for most farmers 
there is only one potential buyer for their produce and these 
monopolies are destroying the countryside 
late monday the sejm passed by a 33529 vote legislation 
designed to blunt inflation the law provides income compensation 
for up to 80 percent of the increase in the cost of living 
the program that takes effect today includes abolishing meat 
ration coupons which since 1981 permitted each family member the 
right to buy 5 pounds of meat monthly from stateowned shops at 
controlled prices 
consumers always could buy additional meat at higher prices from 
private stores but it was too expensive for many in effect all 
meat will now be at or near the freemarket price 
for example 22 pounds of rationed pork roast might cost 120 
if a consumer was lucky enough to find it in a state store but 
590 to 950 at a farmers bazaar the average monthly salary is 
about 127 
some food items still will be subject to price controls bread 
lowfat milk cottage cheese and milk products for infants the 
government said 
