the united states should put greater effort 
into helping cool or avoid conflicts among developing nations says 
a congressional report that rates problems in third world countries 
as a greater threat to us security than the soviet military 
the danger points can become turning points toward improving 
life for all on this planet especially the poor and hungry if 
we act now rep mickey leland dtexas said tuesday at a news 
conference where he joined two other lawmakers in releasing the 
report 
it lists five major problems in developing nations economic 
stagnation environmental damage the threat to democracy from the 
militarys political power weapons proliferation and drug 
trafficking 
in one major recommendation the report by congress arms 
control and foreign policy caucus calls for all nations to cut 
their military budgets by 50 percent providing money for urgent 
civilian needs 
the report also suggests that the united states press for 
negotiated settlements to civil wars and urges a us ban on 
military aid to countries with dictatorships or to those ruled by 
military forces that act independently of elected governments 
the united states cannot concentrate alone on the outdated 
eastwest cold war mentality according to the study 
todays security threats are problems like global warming and 
international debt said rep matthew f mchugh dny another 
congressman involved with the report 
they arent american or soviet problems alone and they cant 
be solved bilaterally they are transnational problems that 
require transnational solutions 
leland noted that wars have an economic as well as personal 
cost saying that last year the 23 wars in the developing world 
not only killed hundreds of thousands of people and created 
millions of refugees they also reduced us exports by billion of 
dollars 
the report also recommended the appointment of a cabinetlevel 
us development representative similar to the us trade 
representative to concentrate on the problems of developing 
nations and it called for a summit between developed and 
developing countries 
sen mark hatfield rore a member of the caucus said the 
five global epidemics may not explode as fast as nuclear weapons 
but their net effect could be just the same destruction of our 
society as we know it 
the report said the five major third world problems it focused 
on are emerging as a potentially greater longterm threat to us 
security than soviet military power 
