a persistent housing slump helped push 
construction spending in june to the lowest level in eight months 
the government said tuesday but economists are expecting at least 
a modest rebound as interest rates decline 
the commerce department said residential nonresidential and 
government construction activity fell 08 percent in june to a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4147 billion the lowest level 
since october the decline followed a 06 percent gain in may and a 
08 percent drop in april 
construction of new housing units dropped 12 percent to an 
annual rate of 1366 billion the lowest level in three years it 
was the fifth consecutive monthly decline 
a yearlong campaign by the federal reserve board to fight 
inflation with higher interest rates ended this spring starting in 
early june the central bank reversed course and has eased 
shortterm rates three times once in june and twice last month 
longterm rates over which the fed has less influence are also 
down thirtyyear fixedrate mortgages averaged 981 percent last 
week the lowest in two years according to the federal home loan 
mortgage corp 
economists expect rates to continue falling gradually and as a 
result construction activity to pick up but softness in economic 
growth overall will prevent a strong surge they said 
i dont see a big rebound at least in the housing sector 
i think we have several more slow months to come while people wait 
to see whether were going to have a recession or not said 
economist james christian of the us league of savings 
institutions 
if you cant sell them you shouldnt build them he said 
activity for the first six months of the year was only 29 
percent above the same period in 1988 an increase that doesnt 
even make up for inflation in construction costs 
the weakness in june included a 48 percent drop in public 
construction which accounts for about onefifth of construction 
activity to an annual rate of 806 billion the decline included 
a 36 percent drop in spending for highways and streets the 
biggest government category 
spending on singlefamily homes fell 13 percent to an annual 
rate of 1136 billion while multifamily construction was down 09 
percent to 23 billion 
nonresidential construction rose 28 percent to a rate of 
1003 billion that reflected strength in industrial projects up 
43 percent hotels and motels up 68 percent office building up 
18 percent and other commercial projects such as shopping 
centers up 25 percent 
