the department of energy should slow its plans 
for a proposed highlevel nuclear waste dump in nevada and make 
studying the risk of earthquakes and volcanic eruptions a high 
priority the nuclear regulatory commission staff said today 
the nrc staff made public its comments on the departments site 
characterization plan designed to determine whether the proposed 
yucca mountain repository located about 100 miles northwest of las 
vegas could safely store tons of radioactive nuclear waste for 
10000 years 
nrc has a broad programmatic concern that the pressure to meet 
unrealistic schedule milestones may leave doe insufficient time to 
plan and to execute proper technical informationgathering 
activities said robert bernero chief of waste disposal for the 
commission 
in a letter to sam rousso acting director of civilian 
radioactive waste management for the energy department bernero 
also expressed concern about geologic faults and volcanic cones in 
the area 
high priority should be given to conducting those 
investigations which can lead to a determination of whether the 
site is subject to an unacceptably high probability of disruption 
as a result of volcanism faulting or seismicity bernero said 
at a briefing at nrc headquarters in nearby rockville md 
bernero said the volcanic cones in the area of yucca mountain have 
been a cause of concern for nrc experts 
you cant miss them he said if you stand on the 
mountain thats what you see 
bernero also said in his letter that the department needs to 
demonstrate the adequacy of its design for an experimental shaft 
to be drilled on the proposed site which he said would probably be 
used for ventilation and other purposes 
the department also needed to improve its program to assure 
quality of performance by contractors he said 
the nevada state government is strongly opposed to the waste 
dump for safety and public health reasons gov bob miller recently 
signed a bill prohibiting storage of highlevel radioactive waste 
in nevada 
