<TEXT>
a national drug strategy presented to cabinet 
officers focuses on law enforcement and stresses a need to rid 
inner cities of illegal drugs according to administration 
officials who have seen the document 
the predominant theme is the inner city one administration 
source who spoke on condition of anonymity said tuesday 
a paramount target of lawenforcement activity especially at 
the local level must be the disruption of those street markets for 
drugs in which retail demand and supply finally meet in a 
combustible mix the report said according to a source 
the strategy report required by the 1988 antidrug law that 
created the office of national drug control strategy strongly 
reflects public comments made by director william j bennett since 
he took office five months ago the final report is due sept 5 
it reads like one of his speeches said one source 
bennett has said repeatedly that the war against drugs must be 
fought on all fronts enforcement prevention and treatment and 
that the nation must do more and do better on each of those fronts 
the report reflects that attitude 
no single strategy pursued alone or to the detriment of other 
possible and valuable initiatives can work to contain or reduce 
drug use the strategy says 
what that means in terms of money was not immediately clear as 
the draft strategy circulated monday included no budget figures 
that might reflect the exact priorities it also did not include a 
classified strategy on international and interdiction policies that 
is under review by the national security council 
in an interview in june bennett said he expected to call for 
more money for drug treatment and probably more for prevention 
asked whether that meant less proportionally for law enforcement 
he said no not necessarily 
last week bennett said the escalating cost of the drug war may 
eventually lead to the need for a tax hike 
the strategy focuses on the highlyaddictive smokeable form of 
cocaine called crack and denounces any move to decriminalize any 
kind of illegal drug despite some officials claims that such 
action might cut down on drugrelated violence 
legalizing drugs would be an unqualified national disaster 
the report says in fact any significant relaxation of drug 
enforcement for whatever reason however wellintentioned would 
promise more use more crime and more trouble for treatment and 
education efforts 
instead the report says we should be tough on drugs much 
tougher than we are now 
the new york times reported on the strategy in tuesdays 
editions 
the strategy reflects bennetts past statements that education 
and treatment programs must be tied to strong law enforcement to be 
effective on numerous occasions bennett has told of treatment 
specialists who say arrests of drug users are what spur them into 
treatment and keep them there 
the strategy includes proposed antidrug legislation for states 
that closely resembles outlines bennett provided two weeks ago to 
the american legislative exchange council a gathering of state 
legislators at monterey calif according to one source 
at the meeting bennett urged the legislators to take a range of 
actions from hiring more police judges and prosecutors and 
building more prisons to ensure certain and prompt punishment of 
drug offenders to imposing civil fines of up to 10000 for those 
convicted of possessing small amounts of drugs 
bennett has warned that states and educational institutions that 
fail to impose some antidrug laws could risk losing federal money 
in the most recent stategy draft that threat takes the form of 
a possible loss of highway funds for states that fail to revoke 
drivers licenses from those convicted of drug offenses 
the draft also threatens to drop federal education funds from 
elementary secondary and postsecondary schools that fail to have 
education departmentchecked and approved drugprevention programs 
and policies threats in an earlier draft to revoke criminal 
justice funds were eliminated from the later draft 
