<TEXT>
cuts during recent years in a federal program 
that provides housing for the elderly and handicapped left a long 
waiting list of applicants for available units according to an 
american association of retired persons study released tuesday 
the department of housing and urban development scaled back the 
socalled section 202 construction during the reagan administration 
and scrapped elevators for twostory buildings housing frail 
residents the study said 
although aarp cited the program as a model of successful 
cooperation between the federal government and private nonprofit 
sponsors it said it found newer units inadequately adapted for 
residents whose mobility decreases with age 
over half of the projects occupied during the most recent 
phase of the program were forced by hud to change their 
construction plans to eliminate congregate spaces or elevators to 
use lower quality construction materials or to build smaller 
units said john rother aarps director of legislation research 
and public policy 
this raises questions about the ability of these projects to 
remain sound and able to adapt to the residents needs 80 percent 
of whom are elderly women he added 
aarp said that hud since 1959 has provided direct lowinterest 
loans to nonprofit sponsors to encourage construction of 
subsidized rental housing for older adults and the disabled it 
added that nearly 200000 units have been built since the program 
began but new construction has decreased from 20000 units in the 
1970s to 10000 units last year 
it said waiting lists averaged eight people for every vacancy in 
buildings constructed with section 202 funds 
the organization advocates a larger section 202 construction 
program to keep the elderly and handicapped out of more expensive 
institutional care 
aarp a nonpartisan organization representing people age 50 and 
older said surveys were mailed to all the section 202 housing 
project managers and sponsors in 1988 of whom about 60 percent 
responded 
rep james florio dnj chairman of the subcommittee on 
housing and consumer interests of the house select committee on 
aging released the study conducted by the university of illinois 
and called it a useful tool to motivate congress on housing 
legislation 
needless to say the current crises at the department of 
housing and urban development have taught us that better monitoring 
of program administration and effectiveness is severely needed 
he said 
florio said that if the federal government does not authorize 
additional construction lowincome older adults will not live 
long enough to move from the waiting lists into 202 units 
</TEXT>
