<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan 
calling the low us savings rate one of the most critical problems 
facing the country said tuesday that the bush administration is 
drawing up legislative proposals to encourage americans to be more 
thrifty 
the low rate of savings in the united states compared to other 
industrial countries has been a major source of concern for 
policymakers trying to make american businesses more competitive 
internationally 
personal savings as a percentage of disposable income fell to 
a record low of 32 percent in 1987 and recovered only slightly to 
42 percent in 1988 
the fed chairman said that between the civil war and world war 
i the united states had the highest savings rate in the world a 
position now held by japan policymakers are concerned because a 
low pool of savings drives up the cost of borrowing for businesses 
making it more expensive for them to expand and modernize their 
production facilities 
greenspan testifying before the senate banking committee 
called the low us savings rate the crucial issue for the 
longterm economic outlook of the country 
he said officials at the federal reserve the treasury 
department and the presidents council of economic advisers were 
studying a variety of possible legislative proposals to boost 
savings 
treasury undersecretary robert r glauber said in an interview 
that the administration had a task force reviewing the low savings 
question glauber said one option being considered was revamping 
individual retirement accounts which were scaled back in the 1986 
tax law 
also being studied glauber said were ways to eliminate the 
inequity in the tax code that corporations face between borrowing 
to finance expansion and selling more equity in their concerns if 
a corporation raises capital by borrowing it can deduct its 
interest payments but if it sells stock in the company and 
distributes dividends on its profits both it and its shareholders 
are taxed on those profits 
glauber said treasury secretary nicholas brady would be 
addressing the countrys inadequate savings rate during a series of 
speeches this fall the administrations push for a reduction in 
the capital gains rate would be included as one of the changes 
needed to lower the cost of capital to businesses glauber said 
these are issues on which the secretary feels very strongly 
glauber said 
one problem the administration faces in proposing any changes in 
the tax law is that creating tax breaks to encourage savings such 
as restoring the full deductability of ira contributions would 
cost the government billions of dollars at a time of high budget 
deficits 
greenspan said americas low savings rates were a very 
difficult problem one that has exasperated economists for a number 
of years 
on other subjects greenspan 
confirmed that the central bank moved to lower interest rates 
for a third time last week as part of its continuing effort to keep 
the country out of a recession 
predicted that the us trade deficit would show little further 
improvement this year because increases in the dollar would hurt 
american exports but greenspan said he believed the trade deficit 
would resume dropping significantly beginning next year 
backed the administrations position that the huge bailout of 
the savings and loan industry should be handled offbudget 
this approach because it would be harder to duplicate would not 
encourage other efforts to circumvent the grammrudman deficit 
reduction law requiring a balanced federal budget by 1993 
greenspan said 
rejected suggestions that the grammrudman deficit targets 
which call for reducing the shortfall to 64 billion in 1991 and 
28 billion in 1992 should be raised saying any such tinkering 
would roil financial markets 
greenspans comments on the deficit targets came in response to 
a question from senate budget committee chairman james sasser 
dtenn 
sasser later told reporters that he opposed changing the 
grammrudman targets but that the idea was being floated by other 
lawmakers who wanted to avoid the pain of making sharp cuts in the 
federal budget next year right before the midterm congressional 
elections 
he said the suggestion was being made in connection with 
proposals to remove certain big government programs such as social 
security and highway construction from the main federal budget 
