<TEXT>
highdefinition television is unlikely to be 
the salvation of the us electronics industry predicted by its 
boosters according to a report tuesday that instead pictured hdtv 
as a small fish in a big hightechnology pond 
the congressional budget office report said hdtv proponents have 
made very optimistic forecasts about big a market the next 
generation of video will gain the cbo also said that even under 
the rosiest forecasts hdtv sales will be small compared to other 
electronic equipment markets 
the cbo report said it was questionable how quickly consumers 
would accept hdtv which promises images with quality approaching 
those of 35mm motion pictures particularly if there are cheaper 
types of advanced tv receivers available 
it discounted claims that hdtv will drive the technology of the 
us electronics industry the cbo said the total world market for 
electronic equipment grew by 54 billion in 1988 to reach 461 
billion and the world market for hdtv receivers and vcrs is 
forecast to be less than 30 billion by the year 2010 
hdtv also will spur only marginal production of sophisticated 
memory chips which are widely used in other applications even now 
the report said 
for hdtv to add much to chip technology would be a case of the 
tail wagging the dog the report said 
nevertheless the report said government support of hdtv 
research might be justified by reason of increased employment 
national prestige or scientific advancement 
written by philip c webre the report was introduced at a 
hearing of the senate governmental affairs committee that is 
considering a possible government role in fostering the growth of a 
us highdefinition tv industry proponents say a quick government 
decision is vital in overcoming the japanese and european lead in 
the hdtv arena 
committee chairman sen john glenn dohio said the united 
states needs to preempt foreign competition on the product 
invented in this country 
in other hdtv developments tuesday 
the senate commerce science and transportation committee gave 
voice vote approval to a 305 million authorization bill for the 
commerce departments new technology administration in fiscal 1990 
the bill essentially doubles spending for the departments national 
institute of standards and technology and includes 75 million for 
nists internal lab work on advanced tv and 30 million in seed 
money to spur industrialled hdtv consortia 
the bill was amended to allow foreign companies to participate 
in the hdtv research consortia 
a house science space and technology subcommittee approved an 
amendment to the nist authorization bill to provide 100 million 
annually for three years for creating publicprivate consortia for 
hdtv development 
peter mccloskey president of the electronic industries 
association applauded the cbo report and said it would help shift 
the discussion from just hdtv to the need to find solutions for 
major economywide problems of primary importance to national 
competitiveness 
he said the real impact of hdtv will be on industries in which 
the united states already is a leader such as fiber optic 
communications movie and entertainment creation transmission and 
delivery systems 
tom long representing the american electronics association 
said the cbo report was narrowly focused on hdtvs potential 
use in home tv receivers long said hdtv would be a far more 
important technology driver in engineering workstations and 
personal computers and for development of better manufacturing 
techniques 
the aea has proposed a package of federal support for hdtv that 
would include 1 billion in loans and loan guarantees for 
manufacturing facilities and 300 million over three years to 
expand the 30 million already allocated to the defense advanced 
research projects agency for hdtv research 
the bush administration wants to spur hdtv through lower capital 
gains taxes a permanent tax credit on research and possible 
antitrust exemption for joint industry ventures 
</TEXT>
