29 cars of the 100car train derailed monday several cars 
including the fuelcarrying tankers went down the 100foot 
embankment into whitefish lake no injuries were reported 
burlington spokesman gus melonas said the company was using 
containment booms to stop the fuel slick from spreading further it 
will take about four days to pump the fuel off he said 
melonas did not know how much fuel had leaked into the lake a 
popular recreation site but said the tankers were full when the 
train derailed 
workers were using wooden pegs and other material to slow the 
leakage 
they were actually using limbs and whatever they could put 
their hands on to plug the holes said roger jacobsen a 
burlington operations manager 
the spilled fuel covered an area two miles long and nearly a 
halfmile wide said whitefish city attorney tom muri 
gov stan stephens planned to tour the area wednesday morning 
he declared a state of emergency on monday 
the derailment occurred just as the train emerged near the west 
shore of the lake burlington officials said an empty box car in 
the middle of the train derailed before the train entered the area 
it became wedged sideways in a narrow rock cut like a cork in a 
bottle and cars behind it jackknifed and then popped loose once 
they emerged from the cut above the embankment 
twentyone of the cars were empty melonas said of the eight 
remaining cars five contained diesel fuel and three were carrying 
lumber 
melonas said officials hoped to reopen the track wednesday 
