<TEXT>
in a country where a steak and a 
bottle of wine were on practically every table every day thousands 
now eat at soup kitchens or go hungry in a nation blessed with 
natural resources unemployment and poverty are soaring 
middleclass argentines among the most affluent in latin 
america at one time are so strapped now that they are selling off 
heirlooms that had been in their families since the days when beef 
and grain made argentina one of the worlds wealthiest nations 
this country had no limit said analyst enrique zuleta 
looking back on those prosperous times this was the only country 
where poor people were fat 
where did argentina go wrong 
the most widely accepted explanation is the collapse of the 
statedominated economic system laid down by juan d peron in late 
1940s when argentinas treasury was filled with gold 
now it is in the hands of his successors in the peronist 
movement to rescue the nation 
the problem is very clear to us says sen carlos tenev of 
the governing peronist party which now is trying to sell companies 
it nationalized in the early days of peron the state is very 
weak geriatric the productive apparatus is totally wasted 
warning lights already were blinking when middle class 
argentines flew to beaches in brazil for summer vacations last 
january and february the fiscal deficit was soaring the austral 
currency was tremendously overvalued foreign currency reserves 
were running low 
but such things have happened often in recent years and the 
significance was dismissed what was in store for argentines turned 
out to be even worse than the depression of the 1930s 
when the central bank on feb 6 stopped selling us dollars 
argentines frantically bid up the price at exchange houses in six 
months the austral lost 97 percent of its value inflation doubled 
and then doubled again in july it was running at a monthly rate of 
at least 200 percent 
real wages contracted by onehalf unemployment unofficially 
stands at a record 14 percent an estimated one in four argentinas 
31 million people lives in poverty 820000 people in buenos aires 
province alone eat at least one meal a day at some 1500 soup 
kitchens that have opened according to gov antonio cafiero 
in late may lootings of food stores nationwide prompted the 
government then headed by president raul alfonsin to declare a 
state of siege and suspend civil liberties for one month while 
there have been no major clashes with police since sackings and 
arrests have continued 
few argentines had seen anything like this before 
i dont think anyone thought things would collapse so 
quickly said angel pena an economist with the mediterranean 
foundation research group and the bottom he said may not have 
been reached 
economic collapse was waiting to happen 
annual inflation has been tripledigit in 14 of the past 15 
years the national budget usually is severely in deficit the 
gross national product has remained in stagnation at about 80 
billion the informal economy has blossomed private argentine 
money stashed in safer havens abroad may total 30 billion 
the country was starved of resources said marcos victorica 
director of the institute of contemporary studies it paid its 
expenses by printing money until inflation got out of hand 
payments havent been made in 15 months on the foreign debt of 
64 billion the thirdhighest among developing countries 
maintenance on thermal electricity plants lagged so badly that a 
drought touched off an energy shortage that has lasted since 
december the start of the southern hemispheres summer 
the government stopped capital expenditure stopped research 
stopped maintenance said diana mondino a professor at the 
argentine center for macroeconomic studies a business school 
the government just stared at what was going on wondering what 
to do 
president carlos menem who took office july 8 cannot defer 
hard choices by borrowing abroad or waiting things out as did 
alfonsin his predecessor in his first week as president menem 
increased statecontrolled transport telephone electricity and 
gas rates by 200 to 600 percent 
a gallon of gas jumped immediately to the austral equivalent of 
165 from 23 cents while average monthly incomes remained in the 
40 to 200 range 
noticeably fewer cars were on buenos aires broad boulevards and 
cobblestone sidestreets 
it looks like saturday a taxi driver said on a recent 
weekday morning 
most people cant afford taxis either fares have soared 
sixfold 
similar increases in the prices of food cigarettes movie 
tickets and clothes have produced waves of shock anxiety 
frustration and resignation among argentines particularly the 
middle class 
</TEXT>
