<TEXT>
a new yorkbased commodity futures trading 
concern philipps brothers inc and three affiliates have agreed 
to pay a record 4 million in penalties to settle federal 
allegations of fraud in cocoa futures contracts 
philipp brothers is a wholly owned subsidiary of salomon inc 
which controls the venerable wall street investment firm salomon 
brothers but federal officials stressed that present management at 
salomon was not involved in any alleged wrongdoing 
company and federal officials also said the allegations released 
monday had nothing to do with an ongoing investigation into trading 
practices at commodities exchanges in chicago 
the commodity futures trading commission which regulates us 
futures markets has been criticized in recent months for allegedly 
lax enforcement of regulations at the nations futures exchanges 
critics point to the twoyear undercover justice department 
investigation of alleged trading fraud in the chicago exchanges 
which reportedly could lead to scores of indictments against 
traders and others 
in announcing the settlement monday dennis klejna director of 
the cftcs enforcement division said it represented by far the 
largest civil penalty ever imposed by this commission 
the cftc charged in a 19count administrative complaint that 
philipp brothers and others engaged in several deceptive practices 
from july 1981 to september 1984 
but the essence of the case said klejna was the practice known 
as bucketing 
in bucketing a broker misrepresents trades by buying or selling 
futures contracts away from the floor of a futures exchange while 
indicating to the customer that the trades were made on the 
exchange all futures transactions are required by law to go 
through an exchange 
the alleged practice resulted in 165 million in fees for the 
firm that it should not have earned the cftc said 
philipp brothers in a statement issued in new york said the 
firms current management brought the alleged violations to the 
attention of the cftc after an internal investigation 
the trading practices that led to the settlement were 
terminated in the summer of 1984 and the employees involved were 
discharged at that time no present employees of the company were 
involved said a company spokesman robert f baker who said the 
alleged activities occurred before philipp brothers became a 
subsidiary of salomon 
the cftc charged that philipp brothers told customers their 
trades were being handled on the coffee cocoa and sugar exchange 
in new york when the trades actually were handled off of the 
exchange floor 
customers never really held a futures position on the 
exchange said klejna they thought they did when in fact they 
had orders that were booked at the firm 
while the traders in question werent providing the service they 
claimed to be providing the customer nevertheless was required 
to pay the same commissions fees and margin collateral deposited 
to buy futures charged for properly executed transactions and 
positions according to the complaint 
about 100000 cocoa futures were bought or sold in this manner 
carrying commission fees of about 16 each or a total of 165 
million said klejna 
the commission also alleged that philipp brothers and others 
entered into improper prearranged trades and fictitious sales and 
failed to accurately prepare order tickets 
in addition to philipp brothers three affiliates phibro corp 
and philipp brothers commodities corp both of new york and cocoa 
merchants ltd of london settled the allegations without 
admitting or denying guilt said klejna 
five former employees of philipp brothers were charged in the 
complaint and have not yet settled with the cftc anthony hd 
weldon of london daniel f tulig of sparta nj peter gilliam 
of surrey england esther lander greenfield of monsey ny and 
mark glowatz of east meadow ny 
the alleged violations occurred during primarily on behalf of 
commercial customers said klejna 
</TEXT>
