massachusetts got 50000 for a 
mercedesbenz it seized and auctioned in its corporate tax fight 
with the west german luxury auto maker but that will do little to 
resolve the 7 million in taxes it claims the company owes 
the red fourdoor mercedes sel 560 was valued at 74000 but 
fetched only the minimum bid of 50000 at an auction monday the 
cars owner was mercedesbenz of north america inc until the state 
took possession of the car on july 6 from the home of a company 
employee 
the people who bought it got a very good deal on it said 
betsy houghteling a spokeswoman for the state department of 
revenue 
massachusetts officials allege that mercedes owes the state 71 
million in delinquent corporate taxes the company disputes that 
claim but has failed to appear in massachusetts courts on the issue 
the state is preparing to take the case to courts in new jersey 
where mercedes north american corporate headquarters are located 
houghteling said the states usual strategy in corporate tax 
cases is to seize the assets of a company but beyond an occasional 
employee car mercedes has few assets in massachusetts dealerships 
are independent operations 
mercedes spokesman ab shuman said tuesday that mercedes has no 
formal operations in massachusetts 
in those states where we do have operations we pay our full 
taxes the business in massachusetts is interstate commerce and 
that is exempted from this kind of taxation shuman said 
the massachusetts revenue department argues however that 
although mercedes has no corporate headquarters or major facilities 
in massachusetts it has employees there and makes money by selling 
cars to massachusetts dealers 
the tax case against mercedes began in 1985 as an investigation 
of delinquent taxes against several foreign car manufacturers the 
others in the case have paid their debts and are abiding by the 
states position on taxation because those cases are settled the 
revenue department does not release the names of the companies 
weve collected 10 million from those other companies and 
mercedes is the only holdout houghteling said it would be 
fair to say that mercedes position is unique in the industry 
massachusetts is closely watching cases in other states in which 
revenue departments try to collect taxes merely on the basis of a 
companys advertising in that state 
you dont need to have your company headquarters in a state to 
be found to be doing business there houghteling said 
shuman declined to comment on the seizure of the fourdoor 
mercedes in massachusetts but criticized the revenue department for 
its pejorative language in discussing the tax case 
were made to look like scofflaws he said 
houghteling said most of the 50000 will go into the state 
general fund but the amount may be largely symbolic because the 
state may have to pay thousands to fight its legal battle against 
mercedes for the rest of the back taxes 
