<TEXT>
international paper co has agreed to pay 
fines totaling 990000 and has installed 45 million worth of 
airpllution equipment at a local mill under a proposed consent 
decree with the state and federal governments officials announced 
tuesday 
the fine is the largest environmental fine ever levied in maine 
and the stiffest ever imposed in new england for violations of the 
federal clean air act state and federal officials said 
it used to be that dirty air had to be suffered by all maine 
people so that some corporations might prosper this settlement is 
an indication that those days are over maine attorney general 
james e tierney said at a news conference at which the agreement 
was announced 
state environmental protection commissioner dean c marriott 
portrayed the settlement as only the latest result of his 
departments steppedup efforts to crack down on polluters 
theres more to come he told reporters 
the company which denied all the allegations issued a brief 
statement noting that the agreement is still subject to approval by 
a federal judge and that the alleged violations occurred during the 
late 1970s and early 1980s 
none of the situations which are alleged to have been 
violations are recent or ever posed a danger to the health and 
wellbeing of our employees or surrounding community members 
said richard white a spokesman for international papers jay mill 
international paper based in purchase ny is the largest 
us paper producer 
at issue in the case which dates back to 1983 is a waste fuel 
incinerator that is the largest source of particulate emissions at 
the mill 
the company had planned to restrict the amount of oil burned in 
the incinerator thereby exempting it from tough new source 
pollution standards established under the clean air act but the 
state and federal governments alleged the company repeatedly used a 
greater amount of oil and that emissions from the incinerator 
should be subject to those more stringent standards which cover 
such materials as particulates sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide 
in addition the state had charged additional violations of 
state law including the companys failure to properly monitor 
ambient air quality around the mill 
under the consent decree ip must pay a 540000 fine to the 
state and 450000 to the federal government further the company 
has modified the incinerator to permanently restrict the amount of 
oil it burns and installed 45 million worth of pollution control 
equipment 
ip also agreed to cut emissions of particulates by half and to 
conduct tests next year to determine whether further reductions are 
possible 
tierney stressed that the settlement is unrelated to a state 
lawsuit filed a year ago that alleges widespread violations at the 
mill of many state environmental laws that suit is still pending 
he said 
