<TEXT>
six months after a court settlement in 
the bhopal gas disaster fueled speculation about possible takeover 
attempts union carbide corp said tuesday it has implemented 
poison pill measures to ward off unwanted suitors 
carbide spokesman david n kernis called the antitakeover 
measures routine and said officials at the danbury connbased 
company dont know of any possible takeover attempts and none has 
been offered 
nearly 1000 companies have these things were sure from time 
to time these things have come up for review at carbide but 
obviously this is our first one kernis said 
the poison pill measures announced last week would allow 
carbide shareholders to acquire additional stock at a deep 
discount thereby making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive 
for a potential acquirer 
analysts have said the corporation became a prime takeover 
candidate in february when the supreme court of india ordered the 
multinational chemical giant to pay 470 million to settle claims 
arising from the 1984 bhopal disaster but they were cautious in 
evaluating carbides poisonpill plan 
while immersed in the legal battle over bhopal in 1985 carbide 
successfully fought off a 43 billion hostile takeover attempt by 
gaf corp by repurchasing some of its common stock directors said 
later they never considered a poisonpill defense 
harvey stober an analyst with dean witter reynolds inc said 
monday that carbide is attractive because it has tremendous cash 
flow businesses that can be separated and sold off and it has 
easily understood businesses in addition he said the 
companys stock is currently undervalued closing up of a point 
monday at 2712 
carbide last week reported second quarter earnings of 186 
million or 133 a share on sales of 228 billion the earnings 
were down slighty from 1988 second quarter earnings of 187 
million or 139 a share on revenue of 21 billion 
stober said corporate takeover strategist carl c icahn has been 
mentioned as one possible carbide suitor but stober said he 
believed the company when it said no takeover offers have been made 
its something that many companies have done its usually 
done to get fair treatment under a hostile attempt and usually to 
preclude the use of greenmail he said greenmail is an 
antitakeover maneuver in which the target company buys the raiders 
stock at a price above that available to other stockholders 
leslie ravitz an analyst with salomon brothers inc said that 
carbides action was typical of the chemical industry he said it 
would be misleading to interpret carbides plan as an indication 
that it will soon become involved in an acquisition noting that 
the company has had no suitors in the many months that it has been 
the subject of takeover talks 
ravitz agreed that carbide is an attractive takeover target but 
so is virtually every company out there in the chemical 
industry he said adding that the stock of most chemical 
companies are currently undervalued 
ravitz said carbides poisonpill measures are good only as long 
as the board of directors wants to keep them in place he said if a 
large enough cash offer is made the directors would have to revoke 
measures 
it doesnt preclude a takeover it just gives you a hurdle to 
jump he said 
under the carbide plan shareholders of record as of aug 31 
will receive one right to purchase a share of common stock at a 
discount for each outstanding share of stock they own the rights 
will expire on aug 31 1999 unless redeemed by the company at a 
cost of 1 cent per right 
the rights are exercisable only within 10 days after a potential 
buyer acquires 20 percent or more of carbide common stock or only 
within 10 days of an announcement of a tender offer to acquire at 
least 20 percent of carbide stock 
