<TEXT>
indictments will be announced wednesday 
resulting from the fbis undercover probe of suspected corrupt 
practices and traders at the nations two largest futures 
exchanges law enforcement sources said tuesday 
the justice department said attorney general dick thornburgh 
fbi director william sessions and anton valukas us attorney for 
the northern district of illinois would hold an afternoon news 
conference in chicago wednesday 
the justice department did not give the reason for the news 
conference 
two law enforcement sources in washington and chicago who spoke 
on condition of anonymity told the associated press the news 
conference was being held to announce indictments stemming from the 
twoyear investigation 
one of the sources said wendy gramm chairwoman of the commodity 
futures trading commission also would attend 
the chicago suntimes reported tuesday that several commodities 
traders who have agreed to plead guilty to crimes have been 
bargaining for reduced civil penalties 
a lawyer was not identified told the newspaper said he and other 
attorneys have been negotiating with the cftc to try to minimize 
penalties against their clients 
the commission which regulates the exchanges has the power to 
pull trading licenses levy fines and ban future participation in 
the markets 
eight to 15 traders have agreed to cooperate in the federal 
probe of an estimated 50 to 100 traders engaging in allegedly 
corrupt practices at the chicago mercantile exchange and the 
chicago board of trade the newspaper reported tuesday 
when charges against cooperating traders are announced the 
commission is expected to disclose administrative penalties the 
newspaper said 
meanwhile the merc has brought its own charges against four 
traders in connection with yenpit trades with an undercover fbi 
agent who was part of the federal probe according to the wall 
street journal 
the merc charges represent the third of four possible levels of 
repercussions traders could face if found to have defrauded 
customers or been guilty of wrongdoing according to one lawyer who 
spoke with the associated press 
the four are federal criminal prosecution federal 
administrative penalties disciplinary action by the exchanges and 
consequences from the national futures association which registers 
certain categories of traders and has its own rules and penalties 
for violating them the lawyer said 
lawyers are calling it quadruple jeopardy he said 
merc spokesman andrew yemma declined to comment tuesday on the 
wall street journal report which said the merc charges concern 
prearranged trading in yenfutures contracts expiring in december 
and march 
it is our policy not to comment on an investigation 
until disciplinary action is taken yemma said 
the charges could result in fines and expulsion of traders the 
journal said administrative action by the cftc is likely to be 
similar according to the suntimes 
even traders who cooperate will lose their licenses but may be 
spared enormous fines the suntimes said also traders might 
avoid longterm bans from participating in the markets by 
cooperating 
for traders who arent cooperating with federal prosecutors 
however the trading commission plans to withhold charges until 
after trials end the newspaper said 
anyone convicted is expected to face maximum administrative 
penalties while anyone found innocent of criminal wrongdoing may 
still be liable for civil action based on court testimony 
prosecutors met with about 20 traders lawyers late last week to 
open the way to possible pleabargain arrangements for clients 
facing indictment under the federal racketeer influenced and 
corrupt organizations act 
in the twoyear futures probe fbi agents infiltrated the 
trading floors to gather evidence of suspected illegal practices 
