northwest airlines has told its 5000 pilots 
that management is optimistic a labor agreement can be reached 
despite the breakdown in 29monthlong negotiations 
sl henning northwests vice president for flight operations 
said in the letter mailed late last week that many key issues 
already have been resolved including a guarantee of no layoffs for 
all pilots now employed by the airline and the right to reopen the 
contract if the company changes control 
i am well aware of the frustration that you feel over the 
unusually long period of time this process has taken henning 
wrote 
i share your frustration we must however keep in mind that 
this process has been complicated by the difficulty of combining 
two very different pilot contracts republic and northwest the 
ongoing unresolved seniority integration and the takeover activity 
during the past several months 
an investment group led by los angeles businessman alfred 
checchi recently completed its 36 billion tender offer for 
northwests parent nwa inc and appeared to have won control of 
nwa 
insurance coverage for retired pilots wages and a b wage 
scale for new pilots are among the major remaining issues in the 
negotiations 
northwest has offered a 5year reduced pay scale for new pilots 
at 70 percent of the existing scale the air line pilots 
association wants a 3year scale at an 80 percent rate 
the contract talks broke off last week and alpa has asked the 
national mediation board to declare an impasse so that a 30day 
coolingoff period would begin at the end of 30 days the pilots 
could legally strike 
henning noted that northwest and alpa have agreed to a 94 
percent wage increase in the first year of the contract the wage 
increase for the remaining three years of the contract remains 
unsettled the company has offered increases of 3 percent 2 
percent and 3 percent respectively through 1992 the pilots want 
45 percent 5 percent 45 percent and 2 percent through 1993 
also in dispute is a lumpsum payment to replace retroactive pay 
for the 29 months during which the old contract has been expired 
northwest has offered 5 million to be distributed among pilots 
according to their own formula the pilots are seeking 30 million 
the company remains optimistic that progress can yet be made 
that will ultimately lead to an agreement in these remaining 
areas said henning 
alpa spokesman andy murphy said tuesday that the letter was 
largely factual but he said it overlooks unattractive portions 
of the companys latest offer 
they certainly have painted a brighter picture than we see 
it murphy said for all the highlights there are a lot of 
lowlights and we have problems with some of those things 
